Here's how to implement all three using Shell's navigation guard and back button behavior:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. ViewModel with the back command and dirty-tracking flag:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    public IRelayCommand BackCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(GoBackAsync);
    }

    async Task GoBackAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return; // user chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**3. Guard the hardware/swipe back in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

The custom button handles taps, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that with `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back (Pop) navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation so the user stays on the page.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the custom button tap; `OnNavigating` catches swipe-back and the hardware button.
- To avoid a double-prompt (command + guard both firing), you can set a flag in the VM before calling `GoToAsync("..")` and check it in `OnNavigating`, or simply remove the prompt from one of the two paths.
